Aim:
To learn how to use dictionaries in Python and perform different operations on them.

Algorithm:
Start the program.
Create a dictionary with some key–value pairs.
Display the dictionary.
Add a new key and value to the dictionary.
Access and display a value using its key.
Display all the keys and values of the dictionary.
Remove one element from the dictionary.
Print the updated dictionary.
End the program.

Code:
student = {"name": "Rahul", "age": 20, "course": "BCA"}
print("Dictionary:", student)
student["city"] = "Delhi"
print("After adding element:", student)
print("Student name:", student["name"])
print("Keys:", student.keys())
print("Values:", student.values())
student.pop("age")
print("After removing element:", student)

Output:
Dictionary: {'name': 'Rahul', 'age': 20, 'course': 'BCA'}
After adding element: {'name': 'Rahul', 'age': 20, 'course': 'BCA', 'city': 'Delhi'}
Student name: Rahul
Keys: dict_keys(['name', 'age', 'course', 'city'])
Values: dict_values(['Rahul', 20, 'BCA', 'Delhi'])
After removing element: {'name': 'Rahul', 'course': 'BCA', 'city': 'Delhi'}
